    'topic' => 'Power Pack Lasers',
    'body' => 'In Digest 97, Joni M Virolainen wrote:

> Subject: Power Packs
>
> Now I have this problem with generating power packs to my TL-9 DEI \'laser
> launcher\'. The FF&S rules about that thing are a bit fuzzy for me at least.
>
> My laser\'s EI is 0.1 MJ per shot and I intend to have 50 shot power pack
> (with rof 2). So, what should I do?

	A while ago I wrote an Excel spreadsheet for designing power pack
	lasers, and in the beginning I had some problems figuring out the
	Storage Battery requirements.


	Your laser needs ( 50 * 0.1 = ) 5 Mj storage battery.

	TL-9 batteries can store 0.4 MWh per cubic meter of battery. 1 MWh
	equals 3600 Mj, so the battery contains ( 0.4 * 3600 = ) 1440 Mj/m^3
	= 1.44 Mj/dm^3.

	5 Mj / 1.44 Mj/dm^3 = 3.472 dm^3 of battery

	If the ROF is 2 shots/turn, the whole battery can be discharged in
	( 5 / 2 * 50 = ) 125 seconds. The slowest possible Battery Discharge
	Rate that can be used is the 36-second model that doubles the battery
	price.

	The Power Pack must have the battry, homopolar generator, 20-50% of
	the DEI laser cooling system, and protetctive casing.

	Component	Volume (dm^3)	Weight (kg)	Price (Cr)
	Battery (5 Mj)	  3.472		  6.944		 13.88
	HPG (0.1 Mj)	 10		 20		 20
	Cooler (50%)	  0.5		  1		850
	Casing (AV 1)			  4.192		 41.92
	----
	TOTAL		 13.972 dm^3	 32.136 kg	925.80 Cr

	If powered by generator instead of battery, the power input will be
	( ( 0.1 Mj * 2 shots ) / 5 seconds = 0.04 MW ) = 40 kW.


	As an example of DEI laser weapons:

----

TL-14 10cm Tunable Wavelenght DEI Laser Rifle

Focal Array Diameter: 10 cm
Pulse Discharge Energy:	40 kj (SA5), 13.3 kj (3), 8 kj (5), 4 kj (10),
800 j (50)
