    'body' => 'From: Stefan Matthias Aust:

>My dream-weapon (feel free to design it :-): I think that TL12 G8
 [details omitted]

I\'m working on some design specs -- look for them in a few days. But
don\'t restrict me to 9x50mm ammo; that\'s a rather arbitrary restriction.
Reframe the spec in terms of allowable recoil for the round and how
many rounds of fire are conventient for a soldier to carry (i.e., 
X turns of fire worth of magazines & cartridges should weigh Y kilos
or less).

>As it was an error of Traveller to think that 1970 computer technology
>will not change about the centuries, it is an error to think the same
>about weapon technology.

True.  I\'ve already incorporated Lahti\'s suggested modifiers to receiver &
barrel weight for advanced materials.  I will be tossing out a suggested
modification to his table, however; keep an eye out for it.

>Lasers are another point.  They are completely useless in relation to
>their TL.  If a TL 13 laser can\'t wound a TL12 soldier, I don\'t need
>it.  

Also true.  I haven\'t examined the small arms laser design sequence in 
detail yet -- it is possible that the example weapons were badly designed.

> I\'m no expert but I think there\'ll be enough
>room for improvements (for example to use other metal or ceramics for
>the round or other explosives with more power or mix up the right
>chemicals to melt the armor and so on)

Basic physics give you a problem that gun designers have been trying
to work around for almost exactly 100 years --  more power behind the 
bullet means more recoil means less accuracy in automatic fire mode.
Remember "Every action has an equal and opposite reaction"?  Applied
to a rocket, that gets you off the ground.  Applied to a bullet, that means
recoil momentum must equal the momentum of the bullet --> m*v
More mass (m) to the gun means less velocity (v) to the recoil to 
satisfy the equation -- but more mass for the soldier to lug around.
Alternatively, you can put that (v) to work doing something besides
kicking your shoulder and pushing the barrel up -- cycling the receiver,
or whatever.  We still haven\'t been able to get rid of all of it.

So, okay, maybe you can up impact energy without increasing recoil
or weapon weight excessively.  There is still a fairly solid limit of max.
possible mass per unit volume (depleted uranium penetrators, until
someone finds a cheap source of iridium or osmium, or invents some
exotic superdense material a lot denser than Trav\'s "superdense") 
times max. feasible velocity in atmosphere (i.e., where the penetrator
material burns up from atmospheric friction).  This limit is rather high...

>As I sidenote: I could start thinking that the TNE rules _want_ to
>allow players to wear perfect-protection (tm :-) armors and to allow
>them to "have a good boody fight" again hordes of NPCs whose weapons
>can\'t harm the PCs.  But if that\'s the only thing for what the
>designers thought TNE is good, roleplaying is lost. A fire fight isn\'t
>roleplaying at all IMHO.  

No, but it\'s a lot of fun :-)  Why do you assume that the *usual* case
will be PCs wearing & using cutting edge military hardware vs. the 
usual underequipped NPCs?  The other way around is much more
challenging...  In our Imperial-era games, and even more ancient
pre-Spinward Marches CT games (i.e., GM-designed "Pocket 
Empire" about 12 years ago...), the PCs usually had flak jackets at
best, and one or two ex-Army/Marine goons with CE suits and an
ACR or Gauss Rifle plus RAM grenade launcher.  They were considered
heavily armed.  (And watch out for lunatics firing HEAP grenades 
INSIDE starships...they punch holes in bulkheads :-(  )


                                           -- Cynthia

p.s. Do you use OS/2, too?  I get the impression that OS/2 is popular in
Germany -- a lot of very good OS/2 shareware is coming from Germany.

