    'topic' => ' Challenge 75',
    'body' => '>Has Challenge 75 hit the racks yet?  It seems overdue to me, but I\'m
>not too sure because Traveller stuff tends to come in erratic spurts in
>my neck of the woods...

Well, it was in at the local gamestore here in New Orleans, LA when I picked 
it up Thursday.

Things that stand out:

(1) GDW needs to hire a real editor, like Steve Jackson Games has.

(2) "Undercity" : good idea, incoherent presentation.  Should have been
sent back to the author with instructions to polish up the rough draft he
submitted.
At the very least, a "Referee\'s Synopsis" should be mandatory.

(3) "Operation: Wolf Snare" : a minor nitpick -- why is the RC all that concerned 
about alienating 5000 whole people on a jerkwater planet?  Macon, MS has more
people than that, and Congress doesn\'t seem all that concerned about alienating
THEM.  Grabbing the Corsair, that might be worthwhile, if they\'re all that desperate
for ships.  But, if the RC is that desperate for ships, why doesn\'t Oriflamme (which 
is so proud of its vast hordes of people) build shipyards and start churning ships out?
Okay, so the scenario isn\'t about RC politics.  With some minor reworking, it would
make a great "Lost Worlds Romance".  We already have a "native princess" in the
form of Orchid...

(4) "Karel Rossum" : anyone else catch the joke in his name?  Clue: look up the 
origin of the word "robot".  Nifty character.

(5) "The Long Fall Club" : Gee, should I pull my punches because this is by a fellow
TMLer?  NAHHH!

George, just WHERE is Mikkadhir?  Coordinates in the standard form would be
nice.  Or is this a "drop-in anywhere suitable" sort of place?  If so, you should say so
up front for the benefit of the slower-witted, like myself.  This adventure is one of the
"The NPC patron not only tells you what the mission is, but tells you how to do it" type; I
don\'t like those.  It doesn\'t give the PCs a chance to decide what to do beyond which door
to go in -- roll your dice and move your mice.  It would be a better scenario if the PCs
were allowed to offer their own plans of attack, and save the default NPC plan for if the PCs
fail to come up with a decent plan.  Oh yes, GDW lost your sidebar on re-entry kits.
       Minor nitpicks: How did Ms.Sweeney get off-planet if the TED stole her ship? How does
the inserting ship get close enough to insert you on a re-entry vector without being detected
by the advanced orbital sensor net?  You know, the one that keeps even small craft from 
slipping through undetected.  If there are so few soldiers in the military that the gate guard
"knows everyone in the military by sight", how can they patrol the entire inhabited area?
If there are that few soldiers, why don\'t we just shoot them all and steal the ships unopposed?
(Steve says I should ask you "If the ships are so important to Ms.Sweeney, why isn\'t she
coming along?") How about some stats on the planet?  Not everyone has whatever
supplement this place appears in (if it does), and you should state prominently what
supplements are required to referee this at the beginning of the scenario...
End George harassment.

(6) "Core subsector" - translate 2300AD 3-D Near Space map into standard 2D Traveller
Hex grid.  Pointless waste of two pages.

(7) "The Madness Effect" - good generic Traveller scenario.  I see the author cleverly
made it a New Era scenario by inserting the word "Coalition" in the appropriate places,
and making the origination & destination worlds Eos & Aubaine.  Can actually be 
dropped in anywhere people use jump drive. It\'s refreshing to see a TNE scenario
that does NOT have a Virus or TED or both in it.

(8) FF&S Errata - badly needed. Should correct some of the more spectacular design
"anomalies".  Everyone, read and pencil into your copy of FF&S!  (Steve says the guys
who wrote the errata obviously didn\'t read the errata as one section says to round weapon
short ranges to nearest 10m, and another section gives ranges like 61, 81, etc.)

(9) "Oasis in a New Era" - Anybody remember the Ducy of Oasis from the Shattered
Imperium era?  It\'s baaack!   A nice little pocket empire; large enough to be plausible,
not so huge as to dominate the former Imperial Core in the face of all comers, the way
a certain other "pocket" Empire from the TNE book will.  Unfortunately, it\'s by the same
author that "Undercity" was, and suffers from the same incoherent presentation.  GDW
still needs an editor that knows how to EDIT.

                                                           -- Cynthia



