Q=V*de*c*(t2-t1)+r*m ;V=volume, de=density, c=thermal capacity, t=temperature

                      r=how much energy one kg of water needs to evaporate
                      m=mass
Q=V*de*c*(t2-t1)+r*de*V =>

V=(40 kJ)/(998 kg/m3*4.19 kj/(kg*C)*63C+2260 kJ/kg*998 kg/m3)=1.59E-5 m3 =>

V=0.159 dl = 15.9 cm3
----

Personally I would not want to lose that much from me. My point is that
*if* my calculations are right, then I can safely assume that laser is
just used to boil and evaporate the flesh. As it evaporates very quickly
the reaction is much like explosion.

For now I don\'t have time to calculate how much metal (steel) same laser
could evaporate or even melt.

Please correct me if I\'m wrong.

