    'month' => '11',
    'topic' => 'Left-hand weapons',
    'body' => 'From: Hugh Foster

>Here\'s a thought for you. "Modern" Traveller weapons are bullpup >design,
yeah ? Now, if the receiver\'s back behind the level of the >trigger guard,
that\'s pretty close to the face, hmm ? Isn\'t that gonna >mean that a leftie
is going to get an earful of hot brass everytime he >pulls the trigger ?
Answers on a postcard...

1) "Modern" (TL 8+) Trav weapons use caseless cartridges.

2) That\'s why lefties get left-handed receivers.  Steve cites the
British Individual Weapon, which has two spare parts that are 
swapped out to change from right-handed to left-handed.  Steve
says all Real World bullpup weapons that he knows of come in
right & left-handed versions.

3) You don\'t need to have a bullpup to get a faceful of hot brass
when shooting a rifle offhand.  I\'ve shot both SKS and MAC-90 
(semi-auto AK-47), and they both throw brass all over the place.
I was told of an incident where someone lost an eye shooting a 
right-handed MAC-90 left-handed -- brass case thrown in his eye.
Most Real World guns (not just bullpups) are available in both 
right- and left-handed versions for that reason -- no one likes
cases thrown across their face (or into their face!).

                                                  -- Cynthia


