    'index' => 'an942',
    'topic' => ' Ship designs',
    'body' => '
Thanks for the input so far... we\'ve been discussing it at the office
all weekend.  Just a couple comments/clarifications:

> merrick@RT66.com (Merrick Burkhardt) says:
> 
> >I\'ve been making some 1:1000 scale ship miniatures, as well as bashing
> >some in the same scale from model kits. I have a couple of designs for
> >Zhodani ships based on some earth defense force (Starblazers) ships.

It is important to note that all the SB ships I\'ve bashed have been
changed a fair bit.  I ground the \'flying bridge\' parts off all of them,
and the bridges are a raised bump (like an airliner) on the top front
(it pre-exists on the models).  In addition, I added slightly forward
swept \'wings\' (4 of \'em) arranged like an x-wing from star wars (like
the ship on the cover of The Journal of the TAS #23 (dunno if it was
ever printed... I don\'t have any past #22, but the cover was shown in
the "next issue\' section)

> James Kundert says
> 
>  Based on every Zhodani ship picture to see print, I\'ve seen a few
> consistent factors.
> 
>  -The Zhodani almost always mount maneuver drives as a pair or set of
>   smaller thrusters, instead of one large central thruster.

I hadn\'t noticed this before.  Are there *any* pictures of decent sized
ships (10,000 being barely decent)?  I only wonder since it seems that
smaller ships would be more varied within a culture simply because
they\'re built in more shipyards (as well as by local gov.s for \'coast
guard\' stuff).

>  -The bridge is always in the classic jet airliner spot: Front-High.
>   The bridge is usually built within the basic hullform instead of standing
>   out from it.

Hadn\'t seen this either, but it works for the ones we\'ve played with so
far :)

> 
>  -Overall width of the hull will be greatest on the lower decks. The
>   paired engines are often set in distinct nacelles which form the widest
>   part of the ship (see the Vlezhdatl).

>  -There are three basic hull formats: beveled box (typified by the
>   Vlezhdatl in BL), flowing (The Ninz scout and the Zhdits), and sharp

I\'d be willing to say the Vlezhdatl is the exception if there aren\'t any
other examples :)

>   and needle-like (the Chatl scout and the Stedlas SDB). Of these three,

I haven\'t seen the Stedlas at all (I have most of the CT, some of the
MT, and some of the TNE stuff... but I don\'t have many of the FASA ship
designs which seem to be most of the canon Zho stuff)

>   the boxy form is used mostly for larger ships and the flowing form
>   and needle mostly for the smaller ships. The flowing and needle forms
>   are sometimes combined in one ship (see the Stedlas).
> 
>  -Zhodani ships rarely have flat tails. They are almost always tapered
>   to a point (Zhdits), or have a ridge running across the back (Ninz).
>   Box-form ships have the engines protrude aft slightly, and the main
>   hull will be beveled instead of flat-backed.

If I were to come up with a bunch of designs that we thought were cool,
what do you think the reaction would be given that the observations
you\'ve made are only based on 5-6 ships? (there isn\'t much to work with
here, which is why I wanted some input :)

> 
>  -Many Zhodani ships are "necked" in shape, having a narrow portion
>   between two main hull sections. The proportions of the two halves
>   to each other varies considerably (see Vlezhdatl and Chatl for
>   extremes), but is always either balanced or tail-heavy.

My critters all look tail heavy at this point, too.  Yipee :)

>  -The Zhodani do not gratuitously streamline. If a design does not need
>   streamlining, it won\'t be built with it. Their fleet refueling doctrine

Who would?  On a related note, at the velocities that ships move, sloped
armor (as well as having the ship pointing along its vel. vector) would
help defeat micro (and not so micro) meteor impacts (the impact missile
discussions, along with some simple calculations of the
damage/penetration values for bullet-sized particles at 100km/sec made
us think about this)

>   apparently depends on gas giants, so we can expect capital ships to be
>   streamlined.

I\'d say damn near all military ships that would operate away from fleets
would (BTW, all my Zho ships are military so far)

>  -Ships of the flowing or needle types generally have one or more forward
>   swept fins. These are more common on starships than on subcraft. It
>   is my opinion (backed up by the original Vargr Module) that the Vargr
>   taste in finned ships came from their first contacts with the Zhodani.

I\'ve got these, and they look really cool.

>  -Civilian ships intended for use within the Consulate are rarely armed
>   or capable of carrying arms.

I\'ll keep this in mind.

>  -Civilian ships intended for use within the Consulate rarely have
>   internal security based on bulkhead divisions, as Zhodani are all
>   "completely trustworthy".
> 
> 
>   Those with Brilliant Lances will have recognized some of the
> ship names I\'ve used above. All originated with FASA and the Keith
> brothers many years ago, and can be found in Adventure Class Ships Volumes
> One and Two. The Vlezhdatl appeared in a seperate package from FASA.
>   The oldest Zhodani ship in print is the Shivva Patrol Ship from
> Adventure 4: Leviathan. The edition that I have has a picture that _might_
> be a Shivva, but it is a rather eccentric picture. I prefer to consider
> the Shivva to be unpictured to date.

I agree, yucky picture.  One of my (greatly altered)  EDF Patrol
Cruisers is upwards of 400 tons.  Once I finish the basic hull form,
I\'ll make a mold, and cast it in urathane resin--then I\'ll find out its
volume based on the resin\'s density (it\'s damn hard to do volumes on the
odd shapes, but my upper limit on this one is 550, and the lower is 270
tons--before adding wings and other goodies, so maybe it\'ll be a shiva
:)

> 
>  To answer the specific question, I view the tapered cylinder with flying
> bridge (ala Star Blazers and Captain Harlock) to be a Solomani thing

I kind of agree here, but since we\'re interested in a CT setting (using
TNE stuff) in the Marches, we wanted Zho ships.  The only pic we had
seem to be the majority of the ones you mention, but we didn\'t think
there were enough to make a decent generalization.  I axed the flying
bridge \'cause I thought it looked goofy, and wreaked the otherwise
streamlined shape.

Thanks for the ideas, and once I get some casted up, the stats can
always be altered if they all look wrong for a given region.


-Merrick
