    'id' => '<ed9a51e0@pc173.qsp.co.uk>',
    'date' => 'Mon, 28 Nov 1994 09:38:48 +0000',
    'ts-index' => '1994-11-28.an947',
    'topic' => ' Laser Penetration',
    'index' => 'an947',
    'month' => '11',
    'body' => '     Several people have brought up the issue of Laser penetration, which 
     reminded me of some questions I had when first reading FF&S.
     
     Derek Smith writes that he can\'t get a small arms laser to have a 
     non-nil penetration.  Presumably this is because "Intensities ... of 
     less than ... 0.39 Mj / cm^2 ... have a final penetration rating of 
     nil" (FF&S p129, para. 7C).
     
     In this part of the design sequence, IPR (Inverse Penetration Rating) 
     is calculated as an intermediary step in calculating final penetration 
     rating (it doesn\'t seem to be used anywhere else).
     
         Penetration rating = 1 / IPR.
     
         IPR of less than 0.5 is rounded down to 0, giving a penetration 
     rating of Nil.
     
     This means that lasers can only have fractional penetration ratings, 
     or 1, or Nil:
     
         IPR    Penetration rating
         ----    ----
         3      1/3
         2      1/2
         1      1
         0.499  Nil
     
     It strikes me as odd that a laser couldn\'t have a penetration rating 
     of, say, 2 or 3, like other small arms.  The only thing stopping this 
     in the rules is the statement that an IPR of less than 0.5 gives a 
     penetration rating of Nil.  There is a brief explanation given for 
     this in the rules, but I can\'t follow its logic.  I don\'t know whether 
     this is due to my lack of understanding, or a mistake on the 
     designers\' part.
     
     Throwing caution to the wind (well, you only live once :-)) I propose 
     that the offending statement be thrown out, and IPR should only be 
     rounded if it is going to produce a fractional penetration rating 
     (e.g. IPR of 9.3 rounds to IPR=9 -> Pen=1/9), otherwise the IPR is not 
     rounded, but the final penetration rating IS (e.g. IPR=0.3 -> Pen of 
     3.3 rounds to Pen=3).
     
     Using this proposition, I ran some figures through, to see what I got:
     
         I (Mj/cm^2)  DV  Pen           Hard AV that can be penetrated
         ----  --  ----           ----
         0.0244       8   8 (i.e. Nil)  -
         0.0319       9   7             1
         0.0434       10  6             1
         0.0625       13  5             2
         0.0977       16  4             3
         0.1736       21  3             6
         0.3906       31  2             15
         1.5625       63  1             62
         6.25         125 1/2           lots!
     
     Looking at these figures, it seems possible to design a laser that CAN 
     cut through Battle Dress:
     
         TL14 Battle Dress AV=8.
     
         Laser, I=0.25Mj/cm^2, IPR=0.4 -> DV=25, Pen=3.
     
     Of course, all this hinges on Penetration ratings of >1 being allowed 
     for lasers.  If anyone can explain to me why they shouldn\'t (i.e. why 
     the current rules are right, and I\'m wrong), then please put me right.
     
     
     Cheers,
     Liam McCauley
     
     Liam_McCauley@qsp.co.uk
