Howdy

I\'m gonna post my kinetic energy missile (KEM) rules one of these days when I

get it all sorted out, but the process of playing/writing them out has posed
a few questions...

Basically, the minimum armor values for ships are way too low.  If you assume
a ship might use 25% of its g-turns to accelerate at maximum, then small
ships
might cruise in-system at speeds of around 20 hexes/turn (or 1.2E06 km/hr).
A small pebble would destroy a scout ship at this speed... without question.

So, what to do about armor?  I think that the BSD armors and above should
only be possible to manufacture in large sheets due to the complexity of the
process.  This would eliminate BSD KEAP rounds, but these are easier to lose
than having to rethink all spacecraft designs.  The point of ditching this is
the following idea:  any material of lesser toughness has a penetration
rating
(PR) that is a positive whole number (ie lasers have a PR of 1/10, steel vs.
BSD has a PR of 10 or something).

Or maybe the lower toughness material could be divided into the larger
toughness
to give the PR (SD vs. BSD would have PR of 2, Crystaliron vs. BSD PR=3.5,
Hard Steel vs. BSD PR=14)

The only reason to limit the KEAP rounds is that if we don\'t KEMs will be
*way* too nasty (a 1g ball would seriously hurt a BB at velocities upwards of
20 hexes/turn).

The result of this is that spacecraft can move at a reasonable clip without
being destroyed.  Without something like this you better keep your
scout/courier
ships below 3 or 4 hexes per turn unless you want them dead.

I think this is a reasonable fix.  Whatcha think?


-Merrick
